00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:41.740
&gt;&gt; Larrie Ferreiro: And the
Library of Congress has a,

00:04:41.740 --> 00:04:46.710 position:56%
among many other things, a fantastic
collection of correspondence,

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:52.010
copies of correspondence, between
many of the major actors in France

00:04:52.010 --> 00:04:55.890
and Spain, and then their
American interlocutors,

00:04:55.890 --> 00:05:01.870
which was a significant source
for much of my research.

00:05:01.870 --> 00:05:10.980
So in 1776, America was fighting
Britain in a war for independence,

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:13.520
but without a Navy,
without artillery,

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:15.760
and even without gunpowder.

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:19.880
And only France and Spain, who were
the historical enemies of Britain,

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:23.880
had both the motive and the
Naval and military strength

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:25.600
to be able to defeat the British.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:28.290
So we needed their alliance.

00:05:28.290 --> 00:05:32.950
But they would only do so
if America was seen not

00:05:32.950 --> 00:05:37.520
as fighting a civil war,
but rather as fighting a war

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:39.480
as an independent nation.

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:43.280
John Adams, who was no fan
of foreign interventions,

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:47.890
said foreign powers could not
be expected to acknowledge us,

00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:51.870
until we had acknowledged
ourselves as an independent nation.

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:57.700
And Thomas Jefferson had said
during the debates over the writing

00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:00.140
of the Declaration, the Declaration

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:05.830
of Independence alone could allow
European powers to treat with us.

00:06:05.830 --> 00:06:09.980
So the Declaration was not
written for King George the Third.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:11.620
He had already gotten
the memo [laughter].

00:06:11.620 --> 00:06:17.570
He actually said in October the
previous year that the fighting

00:06:17.570 --> 00:06:23.220
in Lexington, Concord, and
elsewhere, was specifically aimed

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:25.830
at making America an
independent nation.

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:29.580
So he already understood
that, and the Americans knew.

00:06:29.580 --> 00:06:33.390
The Declaration wasn't written
for the American people.

00:06:33.390 --> 00:06:38.630
They had sent their delegates to
Philadelphia quite specifically

00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:47.000
to declare for independence, and to
write a written declaration of such

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.810
which had never been
done before in the world.

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:55.710 position:56%
If you wanted to become independent,
you fought a war, you won,

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:57.700
and you were independent.

00:06:57.700 --> 00:06:59.880
No declaration needed.

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:02.930
So the Declaration of
Independence was, in fact,

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:07.000
an engraved invitation
asking France and Spain

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.730
to come fight alongside us.

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:13.030
Which is why I say in the book that
it was not just the Declaration

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:15.430
of Independence, it was
also the declaration

00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:17.360
that we depend on France.

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:19.930
And Spain too.

00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:22.230
Now, the Americans knew that France

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:26.010
and Spain wanted a
rematch with Great Britain.

00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:30.750
They come out very badly in the
Seven Years War, which had ended

00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:35.920
against Britain in 1763, with
France losing Canada to Britain,

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:38.410
and Spain losing Florida.

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:41.820
Now, France and Spain were
already closely allied

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:43.880
by family and military ties.

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:49.390
It was called the Bourbon Family
Compact, the two kings were,

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:53.120
in fact, directly descended
from Louis the Fourteenth.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:57.300 position:56%
Both nations wanted revenge, [French
word spoken], against Britain.

00:07:57.300 --> 00:08:01.220
And that was actually what
they called the policy.

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:03.410
But they had different goals.

00:08:03.410 --> 00:08:08.050
France wanted to regain the
balance of power in Europe.

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:11.450
Spain wanted to regain Gibraltar,

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:15.460
and drive the British
from the Gulf of Mexico.

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:20.370 position:56%
And both nations had predicted the
American Revolution long before many

00:08:20.370 --> 00:08:23.710
Americans even knew
that it would happen.

00:08:23.710 --> 00:08:26.430
You can see the quote
from the Duc de Choiseul,

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:30.710
who was the French
Foreign Minister in 1767.

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:34.220
Only the future American
Revolution will consign England

00:08:34.220 --> 00:08:36.300
to a state of weakness.

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:39.020
That isn't an "if"
statement, that's a "when."

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:43.500
Because they knew that
this future revolt

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:46.580
in the American colonies
would weaken Britain.

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:50.280
Because of that, they sent
spies and observers to America,

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:53.430
people like the Baron de Kalb
[phonetic spelling] to see

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:55.780
when that would happen
because they wanted to make use

00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:58.460
of that revolution when it happened

00:08:58.460 --> 00:09:01.990
to further their own aims
of weakening Britain.

00:09:01.990 --> 00:09:05.650
That revolution would not
happen for another eight years.

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:10.170
When the fighting began in 1775,
the British Army was supplied

00:09:10.170 --> 00:09:12.980
by gun factories which
would turn out hundreds

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:15.290
of thousands of guns per year.

00:09:15.290 --> 00:09:16.660
The few American gunsmiths

00:09:16.660 --> 00:09:22.130
that there were could produce
perhaps one gun per month.

00:09:22.130 --> 00:09:26.980
We needed weapons from France and
Spain, and France and Spain did,

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:31.060
indeed, provide arms to the
insurgents, but they used merchants

00:09:31.060 --> 00:09:35.740
like the Diego de Gardoqui, and
Pierre Carron de Beaumarchais,

00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:40.050
as front men to disguise the
source of the arms which were

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:45.030
from the British, sorry from the
French and the Spanish governments.

00:09:45.030 --> 00:09:48.980
But the British were not fooled.

00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:55.190
In the end, over 90% of all the
guns used in the conflict came

00:09:55.190 --> 00:10:01.760 position:56%
from overseas, France and Spain, who
also provided 30 billion, with a B,

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:04.920
dollars, equivalent
in aid during the war.

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:11.320
And that doesn't count the other
parts that they helped us with,

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:14.640
which I will get to in a minute.

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:17.020
Beaumarchais worked with
Cyalstine [phonetic spelling],

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:21.990 position:56%
who was the American envoy in Paris,
to negotiate a contract for arms,

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:25.550
and he was doing so even
before news of the Declaration

00:10:25.550 --> 00:10:28.660
of Independence had reached
the shores of France.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:35.670
In 1776 and 1777, five
Beaumarchais ships carried arms

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:42.820
across the Atlantic to supply
15,000 American troops who arrayed

00:10:42.820 --> 00:10:46.680
to meet Burgoyne at Saratoga.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:49.660
And it was these French arms
that turned the tide of battle.

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:51.910
And you can see this
quote from somebody

00:10:51.910 --> 00:10:55.480
who knew what he was talking about,
because he was at the battle.

00:10:55.480 --> 00:10:57.270
Caleb Stark.

00:10:57.270 --> 00:11:01.400
Unless these Beaumarchais arms
had been thus timely furnished

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:06.880
to the Americans, Burgoyne would
have made an easy march to Albany,

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:10.820
and that victory at Saratoga
turned the tide of the war,

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:12.950
because it was the
first major victory

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:15.250
that the Americans
had in the entire war.

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:20.820
Meanwhile, most of the French
and European volunteers who came

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:23.950
to the United States
came to do so in order

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:27.650
to fight their longtime
enemies, the British.

00:11:27.650 --> 00:11:31.410
But along the way, they made
the American cause their own,

00:11:31.410 --> 00:11:35.010
and George Washington came to
depend upon these immigrants

00:11:35.010 --> 00:11:38.470
who got the job done,
as the Hamilton musical

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:42.320
so aptly describes [laughter].

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:46.110
Luis Lebegue Duportail [phonetic
spelling] became Washington's Chief

00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:48.470
Engineer, and Chief Strategist,

00:11:48.470 --> 00:11:52.570
and planned the fortifications
and sieges.

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:57.780
Baron von Steuben put together the
training plan for George Washington

00:11:57.780 --> 00:12:02.760
that made the Continental Army,
previously a collection of militia,

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:06.850
into a consolidated
professional fighting force.

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:10.220
And, of course, the Marquis
de Lafayette commanded troops

00:12:10.220 --> 00:12:11.800
in the southern theater.

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:14.710
He kept Cornwallis
from coming north,

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:18.100
and he eventually followed
Cornwallis all the way to Yorktown.

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:23.380
Now, the Battle of Brandywine
in 1777 was Washington's attempt

00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:27.070 position:56%
to prevent the British from
occupying the capitol, Philadelphia.

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:30.160
But it also was the trial
by fire for these French

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:33.360
and European volunteers,
who up until that point,

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:35.720
had been mistrusted
by the Americans.

00:12:35.720 --> 00:12:40.880
Remember, they had just finished
fighting the French just a decade

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:47.010
earlier, so that would explain
comments like Nathanael Green,

00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:48.930
so many spies in our camp.

00:12:48.930 --> 00:12:56.350
The Battle of Brandywine changed
all that, and it certainly proved

00:12:56.350 --> 00:12:58.130
that they were not spies.

00:12:58.130 --> 00:13:03.050
In fact, they were very brave
and courageous fighters.

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:06.780
The Polish officer,
Pulaski, led a cavalry charge

00:13:06.780 --> 00:13:10.370
that saved the Continental
troops in retreat.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:12.560
Fleury [phonetic spelling],
who was an engineer,

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:16.840 position:56%
was commended for particular
bravery, and in fact, the Army Corps

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:20.140
of Engineers today now
has the Fleury Medal

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:23.940
for courage and boldness.

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:28.630
And Lafayette himself was wounded
while leading an infantry charge,

00:13:28.630 --> 00:13:32.610
and George Washington commanded
his own doctor to treat him

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:34.480
as if "he were my own son."

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:41.410
So after the Battle of Brandywine,
that initial distrust changed

00:13:41.410 --> 00:13:46.430
and turned first into
acceptance, and then into reliance.

00:13:46.430 --> 00:13:52.130
For Greene, so many spies in our
camp relied heavily on both Steuben

00:13:52.130 --> 00:13:56.490
and Lafayette during
his southern campaign.

