the plantations in the Caribbean,

00:15:16.910 --> 00:15:20.000
that thought was unsupportable.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.660 position:56%
So, the American victory at
Saratoga did not convince the French

00:15:24.660 --> 00:15:25.990
to ally with the Americans.

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:30.500
It simply gave Vergennes the
pretext he needed to carry

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:33.370
out the decision he
had already made.

00:15:33.370 --> 00:15:37.490
Now, that treaty which was signed
in 1778 effectively brought France

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:42.490
into the war against Britain,
and it brought the French Navy

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:45.720
to American shores,
and that was key.

00:15:45.720 --> 00:15:48.820
Because any battle with Britain
at that time was always going

00:15:48.820 --> 00:15:52.990
to be a Naval, sorry, any war
with Britain, at that time,

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:56.040
was always going to be a
Naval war, because that is

00:15:56.040 --> 00:15:58.460
where Britain's strength was.

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:00.980
Having the French Navy on
the American shores meant,

00:16:00.980 --> 00:16:06.120 position:56%
for the first time, that the British
could not at their will move troops

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:12.810
from place to place, resupply
them, redeploy arms and munitions.

00:16:12.810 --> 00:16:18.250
It is the reason why the British
had to evacuate Philadelphia,

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:19.800
after only being there nine months,

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:24.290
because they could not risk being
bottled up by the French Navy,

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:26.910
and have to consolidate their
troops in New York City.

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:33.260
Now, at this time, as I mentioned,
Spain was allied with France,

00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:36.220
but they could not take
the risk of going to war

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:39.790
against Britain in early 1778.

00:16:39.790 --> 00:16:44.010
Now, the reason is that they had
a treasure fleet still at sea.

00:16:44.010 --> 00:16:48.010
It was carrying 50
billion, with a B, dollars,

00:16:48.010 --> 00:16:51.220
equivalent in silver from Peru.

00:16:51.220 --> 00:16:54.300
And until that silver
was safely home,

00:16:54.300 --> 00:16:57.680
they could not risk
having the British predate

00:16:57.680 --> 00:17:01.320
on the convoy and capture it.

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:04.340
It was not until the end of 1778

00:17:04.340 --> 00:17:08.330
when the treasure fleet was
safely home that Spain was free

00:17:08.330 --> 00:17:10.880
to go to war with Britain.

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:13.810
Vergennes counterpart, the
Spanish Foreign Minister

00:17:13.810 --> 00:17:17.500
of the Conde de Floridablanca,
had established the Spanish goals

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:20.650 position:56%
of the war, as recovering Gibraltar,

00:17:20.650 --> 00:17:24.380
and driving the British
from the Gulf of Mexico.

00:17:24.380 --> 00:17:28.520
And right after the Treaty
of 1778, between the French

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:34.030
and the Americans, which brought
France into war against Britain,

00:17:34.030 --> 00:17:40.060
Spain offered to mediate between
France and Britain, provided,

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:43.400
provided they got Gibraltar.

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:44.700
But Britain refused.

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:48.760
Now, Floridablanca, in
one of his usual tirades,

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:53.020
considered Gibraltar just this pile
of rocks, which causes problems.

00:17:53.020 --> 00:17:56.750
But for the British, Gibraltar
was a strategic outpost

00:17:56.750 --> 00:18:01.210
that guarded the entrance to the
Mediterranean or to the Atlantic,

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:07.690
depending upon your point of view,
and for that strategic importance,

00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:11.970
Britain, that pile of
rocks called Gibraltar,

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:15.770
Britain effectively
sacrificed all of America

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:19.470
for that strategic
outpost of Gibraltar.

00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:26.790
Now, with Britain unwilling to
negotiate, Spain agreed to go

00:18:26.790 --> 00:18:28.800
into the war alongside France.

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:34.330 position:56%
They would not ally directly with
the Americans for their own reasons,

00:18:34.330 --> 00:18:37.950
but they agreed that
the war could not end

00:18:37.950 --> 00:18:44.370 position:56%
until Britain had recognized the
United States as a sovereign nation.

00:18:47.110 --> 00:18:52.100
The entry of Spain into
the war, alongside France,

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:55.430
fundamentally changed
the nature of the war.

00:18:55.430 --> 00:19:01.150
From a regional conflict in
North America, to a global war.

00:19:01.150 --> 00:19:06.210
And the reason was, is that the
British Navy and the British Army

00:19:06.210 --> 00:19:12.150 position:56%
to some extent, now had to be
spread far thinner around the globe,

00:19:12.150 --> 00:19:16.410
and it was because the
combined Navy of France

00:19:16.410 --> 00:19:18.790
and Spain were overwhelming.

00:19:18.790 --> 00:19:21.990
By itself, the French Navy could
not hope to defeat Britain.

00:19:21.990 --> 00:19:24.300
By itself, the Spanish
Navy could not.

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:29.520
But together, the Bourbon Fleet
was 124 ships of the line,

00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:32.380
those were the major
warships that fought battles,

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:38.930
against Britain's 95 ships, and
Britain was simply overwhelmed.

00:19:38.930 --> 00:19:42.980
So, instead of just attacking
the Americans in North America,

00:19:42.980 --> 00:19:46.140
the British now had
to shield England

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:49.680
from an invasion by
France and Spain.

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:53.040
They had to defend against
the siege of Gibraltar.

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:56.630
They had to defend their colonies
in the Caribbean, their colonies

00:19:56.630 --> 00:20:03.900
in South Africa, their
colonies in India, from attack.

00:20:03.900 --> 00:20:07.640
All of this was happening
in 1779 and 1780,

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:11.450
as the war in the Americas was
coming to its lowest point,

00:20:11.450 --> 00:20:15.920
and you can see from Alexander
Hamilton's despondent comment,

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:19.570
"If we are saved, France
and Spain must save us."

00:20:19.570 --> 00:20:21.950
That the Americans now understood

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:28.150
that winning the war rested
with France and Spain.

00:20:28.150 --> 00:20:31.920
Now, the invasion of
Britain was going

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:34.730
to be always the centerpiece
of the Bourbon strategy.

00:20:34.730 --> 00:20:41.700 position:56%
After Spain had declared war in
1779, the two nations formed a fleet

00:20:41.700 --> 00:20:46.850
of 150 ships, and 30,000
troops to invade Britain.

00:20:46.850 --> 00:20:52.340
That was larger even than the
famous Spanish Armada of 1588.

00:20:52.340 --> 00:20:56.400 position:56%
Now, the planned invasion of Britain
was going to capture Portsmouth

00:20:56.400 --> 00:21:01.270
and Southampton, it was going to
wreak havoc on the British economy,

00:21:01.270 --> 00:21:04.520
and then potentially bring
Britain to the peace table.

00:21:04.520 --> 00:21:11.600
But that expedition was sidelined
by a massive dysentery outbreak,

00:21:11.600 --> 00:21:19.550
which laid low 8,000 men, and which
the French Admiral's son died.

00:21:19.550 --> 00:21:22.780
The Spanish Admiral, because the
French Admiral was, after that,

00:21:22.780 --> 00:21:26.650
incapable of carrying out
orders, the Spanish Admiral,

00:21:26.650 --> 00:21:32.760 position:56%
Luis de Cordova, also tried but with
this many people sick and dying,

00:21:32.760 --> 00:21:39.310 position:56%
he was unable to carry out the
invasion, and it simply fizzled out.

00:21:39.310 --> 00:21:45.030
Now, as a side note to this massive
invasion, as part of the planning,

00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:49.700 position:56%
the French Navy asked this
relatively unknown American captain,

00:21:49.700 --> 00:21:52.760
John Paul Jones, to create
a diversion for the British

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:56.310
by sailing a small squadron
around the British Isles,

00:21:56.310 --> 00:22:01.040
and capture some merchant
ships, hoping that some

00:22:01.040 --> 00:22:04.840
of the British Admirals might
follow him and be diverted.

00:22:04.840 --> 00:22:12.040
Now, no British admiral was foolish
enough to follow John Paul Jones,

00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:15.280
and his diversion was
largely ignored.

00:22:15.280 --> 00:22:18.640
Certainly, it played no part
in the outcome of the battle.

00:22:18.640 --> 00:22:22.560
It certainly did not cause anything
like a panic within Britain,

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:28.630
but there was a battle that
occurred off of Flamborough Head,

00:22:28.630 --> 00:22:33.210
in which John Paul Jones' small
frigate, the Bonhomme Richard,

00:22:33.210 --> 00:22:38.080
was able to defeat a much
larger British frigate,

00:22:38.080 --> 00:22:41.300
which was guarding a
convoy, the Serapis.

00:22:41.300 --> 00:22:44.880
The commander of Serapis
was knighted,

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:47.950
because he did his job,
he protected the convoy.

00:22:47.950 --> 00:22:53.120
The convoy escaped, and a good
British commander was going

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:57.200
to fight his ship until
death to protect the convoy.

00:22:57.200 --> 00:23:01.840
But, for the Americans,
this was a striking moment

00:23:01.840 --> 00:23:04.860
of David vs. Goliath, which stood

00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:09.770
in for the much larger
British and American conflict.

00:23:09.770 --> 00:23:14.250
At that time, it was a sorely
needed shot in the arm.

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:20.750
Now, back in New Orleans,
Bernardo de Galvez was the Governor

00:23:20.750 --> 00:23:22.990
of Spanish Louisiana.

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:26.780
Now, for those of you who
work here in the Congress

00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:30.120
or are frequent visitors to the
Congress, you might recognize

00:23:30.120 --> 00:23:32.190
that portrait on the left.

00:23:32.190 --> 00:23:38.320
Because a copy of that portrait was
hung in the year 2014 at the event

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:44.510 position:56%
of his becoming an honorary
American citizen in the Senate Wing,

00:23:44.510 --> 00:23:50.280 position:56%
first floor, in front of the Foreign
Relations Committee Room, Room S116,

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:52.870
which is all the way on the north
side in case you want to find it.

00:23:52.870 --> 00:23:55.840
So if you want to write that
down [laughter], Room S116,

00:23:55.840 --> 00:24:03.460
Foreign Relations Committee,
North side, Senate Wing.

00:24:03.460 --> 00:24:07.330
Galvez had supplied American
troops in the Western theater,

00:24:07.330 --> 00:24:09.810
which was up along the Mississippi,

00:24:09.810 --> 00:24:13.140
all the way to Fort Pitt,
which is not Pittsburgh.

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:14.440
He supplied them with money.

00:24:14.440 --> 00:24:17.600
He supplied them with arms,
with munitions, with gunpowder.

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:25.100 position:56%
But when Spain declared war in 1779,
he immediately launched a series

00:24:25.100 --> 00:24:28.880
of lightening attacks that
captured the British post

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:32.610
at Mobile, Nachez, and Baton Rouge.

00:24:32.610 --> 00:24:37.830
And then, after several hurricanes
had set him back, in 1781,

00:24:37.830 --> 00:24:43.070
he commanded a joint Spanish-French
force, that captured Pensacola,

00:24:43.070 --> 00:24:46.910
which was the British
capitol of West Florida.

00:24:46.910 --> 00:24:53.500 position:56%
So with Britain out of West Florida,
Spain now ruled the Gulf of Mexico

00:24:53.500 --> 00:24:56.170
and Britain was no longer a threat.

00:24:56.170 --> 00:25:01.040
And because they were no longer a
threat, when a French Naval force,

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:04.990
under the command of the Comte
de Grasse arrived shortly

00:25:04.990 --> 00:25:10.220
after that battle of Pensacola,
he asked the Spanish Navy

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:14.680
to protect the French colonies,
which was his primary job,

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:16.760
while he took his entire fleet

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:21.460
for a short trip northward,
to the Chesapeake Bay.

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:26.490
So it was because of the Battle of
Pensacola that de Grasse was able

00:25:26.490 --> 00:25:33.510
to take his entire fleet north
for the actions that would occur.

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:35.720
Washington and Rochambeau
had learned

00:25:35.720 --> 00:25:38.940
that the Comte de Grasse
was going to the Chesapeake,

00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:42.740
so they raced south from
New York to meet him,

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:46.090
in order to surround
Cornwallis at Yorktown.

00:25:46.090 --> 00:25:48.700
The Comte de Grasse was a
fighting admiral who was beloved

00:25:48.700 --> 00:25:51.580
by his sailors, and
they said of him,

00:25:51.580 --> 00:25:53.910
the Comte de Grasse
stands six foot four,

00:25:53.910 --> 00:25:57.130 position:56%
and six foot five on days of battle.

00:25:57.130 --> 00:26:03.370 position:56%
And yes, since you asked [laughter],
he was one of the ancestors

00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:06.680
of that Rockstar astrophysicist...

00:26:06.680 --> 00:26:07.980
&gt;&gt; Neil-

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:10.580
&gt;&gt; Larrie Ferreiro: Neil de Grasse
Tyson, that's correct [laughter].

00:26:10.580 --> 00:26:15.010
Now, when the Comte de
Grasse met George Washington

00:26:15.010 --> 00:26:16.410
on his Quarterdeck, and by the way,

00:26:16.410 --> 00:26:21.620
George Washington stood two
inches shorter than de Grasse,

00:26:21.620 --> 00:26:25.720
de Grasse embraced Washington and
exclaimed, "Mon petit General!"

00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:29.380
[laughter].

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:32.440
De Grasse's fleet was
landing troops around Yorktown

00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:36.020
when the British fleet, under
Thomas Graves, appeared.

00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:40.260 position:56%
De Grasse quickly sortied his entire
fleet from the Chesapeake Bay,

00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:43.860
and fought off Graves, which
prevented him from resupplying

00:26:43.860 --> 00:26:47.840
or evacuating Cornwallis, and
again, to underline the point,

00:26:47.840 --> 00:26:49.700
it is not clear he would have won

00:26:49.700 --> 00:26:54.870
that battle had he not had
his entire fleet with him.

00:26:54.870 --> 00:26:59.260
The fact that Thomas Graves could
not enter the Chesapeake sealed the

00:26:59.260 --> 00:27:02.320
fate of the British
Army at Yorktown.

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:06.880
Now, the story of Yorktown
is very well-known.

00:27:06.880 --> 00:27:11.120
After Rochambeau and Washington had
led their troops on a quick march

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:15.180
from New York to Yorktown,
they surrounded Cornwallis.

00:27:15.180 --> 00:27:19.390
The siege began October 9, 1781.

00:27:19.390 --> 00:27:24.620
The guns blasted away for five days
while the siege lines advanced.

00:27:24.620 --> 00:27:27.220
French officers directed the siege.

00:27:27.220 --> 00:27:30.610
French officers directed the
placement of the trenches.

00:27:30.610 --> 00:27:33.820
French officers directed
the gunfire.

00:27:33.820 --> 00:27:39.210
The French also suffered twice
the casualties of the Americans.

00:27:39.210 --> 00:27:43.790
Once the French and American troops
had captured British readouts 9

00:27:43.790 --> 00:27:48.310
and 10, the situation for
Cornwallis was untenable.

00:27:48.310 --> 00:27:52.440
So when Brigadier General Charles
O'Hara, who was Cornwallis' second

00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:57.490
in command, came out to offer
the surrender, he saw the victory

00:27:57.490 --> 00:28:01.820
as a French one, and he offered
the surrender to Rochambeau.

00:28:01.820 --> 00:28:05.580
Now, Rochambeau knew it
was a French victory,

00:28:05.580 --> 00:28:12.050 position:56%
but he also knew the moment belonged
to Washington, so, without a word,

00:28:12.050 --> 00:28:14.880
Rochambeau directed
O'Hara to Washington.

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:18.270
Washington was not going to
take a surrender, or rather,

00:28:18.270 --> 00:28:22.980
accept a surrender, from someone
else's second in command, so he,

00:28:22.980 --> 00:28:28.120 position:56%
in turn, gestured O'Hara to his own
second in command, Benjamin Lincoln,

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:32.740 position:56%
who then accepted the surrender,
and the battle of Yorktown was over.

00:28:32.740 --> 00:28:38.240
Now, the battle of Yorktown
was over, but that didn't mean

00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:40.820
that the war had come to an end.

00:28:40.820 --> 00:28:44.260
Vergennes fully understood that,
it is not in the English character

00:28:44.260 --> 00:28:47.410
to give up so easily,
he told Lafayette.

00:28:47.410 --> 00:28:51.720
But even though there were no
more major battles in America,

00:28:51.720 --> 00:28:55.260
after Yorktown, and there
were a number of skirmishes,

00:28:56.270 --> 00:28:59.470
the fighting continued around
the world between Britain

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:01.700
and the Bourbon Alliance.

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:09.040
By this time, 1781, Britain was
fighting five separate nations,

00:29:09.040 --> 00:29:11.030
without an ally to its name.

00:29:11.030 --> 00:29:12.880
They were overwhelmed.

00:29:12.880 --> 00:29:16.720 position:56%
You can see the different conflicts.

00:29:16.720 --> 00:29:18.140
The assault on Gibraltar.

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:24.570
The siege of Gibraltar absorbed
60,000 Spanish troops alone

00:29:24.570 --> 00:29:28.430
in a four-year siege that
ultimately failed, and yes,

00:29:28.430 --> 00:29:30.930
that is a mushroom
cloud over Gibraltar,

00:29:30.930 --> 00:29:34.460
that is how violent the battle was.

00:29:34.460 --> 00:29:39.920
The Dutch Republic was also drawn
into the war for allowing supplies

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:45.850
to go to France, and the
Anglo-Dutch War was very violent.

00:29:45.850 --> 00:29:49.670
France had allied with the
Kingdom of Mysor in India,

00:29:49.670 --> 00:29:54.050 position:56%
in order to drive the British East
India company from the subcontinent.

00:29:54.050 --> 00:29:58.470
That also failed, and the
battles were also violent.

00:29:58.470 --> 00:30:01.910
And in fact, the last
major battle of the war

00:30:01.910 --> 00:30:05.500
of American independence
was the battle of Cuddalore,

00:30:05.500 --> 00:30:08.660
fought in India, and
that happened six months

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:10.270
after the preliminary peace
treaties had been signed.

00:30:10.270 --> 00:30:20.770
The peace of 1783 ended eight
years of war, and during that time,

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:27.380
200,000 French and Spanish soldiers
and sailors fought in the war,

00:30:27.380 --> 00:30:33.240
compared with an estimated
250,000 to 380,000 Americans.

00:30:33.240 --> 00:30:36.920
France and Spain were as in
vested in this war as we were.

00:30:37.940 --> 00:30:41.730
America could never have
won the war without France.

00:30:41.730 --> 00:30:45.070
France could never have
fought the war without Spain.

00:30:45.070 --> 00:30:49.210
So, what I want all of you to take
away from this is the following.

00:30:49.210 --> 00:30:53.890
The United States did not
achieve independence by itself.

00:30:53.890 --> 00:30:56.480
It was, in fact, born
as the centerpiece

00:30:56.480 --> 00:31:00.290
of an international
coalition, which worked together

00:31:00.290 --> 00:31:05.810 position:56%
to defeat a common adversary, and it
is America's role as the centerpiece

00:31:05.810 --> 00:31:08.590
of international efforts
for a common good

00:31:08.590 --> 00:31:13.440
that continues even today
to define the United States

00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:14.780
as the indispensable nation.

00:31:14.780 --> 00:31:16.580
Thank you.

00:31:16.580 --> 00:31:23.170
