&gt;&gt; Larrie Ferreiro: Okay, I have
one question that nobody asked,

01:02:02.520 --> 01:02:05.850
which is why I have this
slide up there [laughter].

01:02:05.850 --> 01:02:07.640
Nobody asked the obvious question,

01:02:07.640 --> 01:02:10.790
and by the way, nobody
has yet done so.

01:02:10.790 --> 01:02:12.830
If Lafayette wasn't the
most important figure

01:02:12.830 --> 01:02:16.110
in this whole story, how come he
is the one who gets all the press,

01:02:16.110 --> 01:02:17.900
and the answer is he
made a grand tour

01:02:17.900 --> 01:02:21.590
of America, 1824, and then he died.

01:02:21.590 --> 01:02:25.190
And sort of like Elvis, you know,
great career move [laughter].

01:02:25.190 --> 01:02:30.520
And I say this because there
is a wonderful portrait

01:02:30.520 --> 01:02:34.020
of Lafayette just before
he passed away.

01:02:34.020 --> 01:02:43.590
He visits all 24 or 22 states,
takes steamboats to a lot of these.

01:02:43.590 --> 01:02:44.890
This I found interesting.

01:02:44.890 --> 01:02:46.990
Eats massive dinners every night,

01:02:46.990 --> 01:02:49.310
I don't know how he
didn't gain weight.

01:02:49.310 --> 01:02:53.820 position:56%
This was when he was called The
Hero of Two Worlds, not before then.

01:02:53.820 --> 01:03:00.050
And even in World War I, Pershing,
1917, his aide to camp said

01:03:00.050 --> 01:03:01.890
"Lafayette, we are here."

01:03:01.890 --> 01:03:05.420
Okay, so that was the event
that cemented Lafayette

01:03:05.420 --> 01:03:09.730
as the centerpiece, and kind of,
you know, put France at least

01:03:09.730 --> 01:03:14.470 position:56%
